# Part 1 – K3s with Vagrant (two machines)

This part sets up a lightweight Kubernetes cluster using K3s on two Alpine Linux virtual machines managed by Vagrant. One VM acts as the server (control plane), the other as an agent (worker).

## Requirements

- VirtualBox (6.1 or later)
- Vagrant (2.2+)
- Internet connection (to download boxes and K3s)

## Directory structure

p1/
├── Vagrantfile          # main Vagrant configuration
├── confs/
│   └── config.env       # environment variables (login, IPs, resources)
└── scripts/
    ├── setup-server.sh  # provisions K3s server (control plane)
    └── setup-worker.sh  # provisions K3s agent (worker)

## Configuration

Edit confs/config.env to match your environment:

LOGIN="your42login"          # used for VM hostnames (yourloginS, yourloginSW)
OS_BOX="generic/alpine318"   # Alpine Linux 3.18 (64-bit)
CPU_COUNT=1
RAM_MB=1024                   # 1GB recommended (512 minimum)
SERVER_IP="192.168.56.110"
WORKER_IP="192.168.56.111"
NETWORK_INTERFACE="eth1"      # host-only network interface inside the VMs

Note: The generic/alpine318 box uses eth1 for the second network adapter. If you change the box, adjust NETWORK_INTERFACE accordingly.

## Running the cluster

cd p1
vagrant up

This will:
- Create and boot two VMs (yourloginS and yourloginSW)
- Install K3s server on yourloginS (with --cluster-init for HA-compatible storage)
- Install K3s agent on yourloginSW and join it to the control plane
- Copy the kubeconfig to the default location (/home/vagrant/.kube/config)

## Verification

After successful provisioning, check the cluster status:

vagrant ssh yourloginS -c "kubectl get nodes"

Expected output:

NAME        STATUS   ROLES                AGE   VERSION
yourloginS  Ready    control-plane,etcd   2m    v1.34.6+k3s1
yourloginSW Ready    <none>               1m    v1.34.6+k3s1

You can also run:

vagrant ssh yourloginS -c "kubectl get pods -A"

## Troubleshooting

- VT-x/AMD-V errors: Enable nested virtualization in your host's VirtualBox VM settings (or run Vagrant directly on a bare metal host).
- Worker fails to join: Check that the node-token file is correctly passed. The token is written by the server into confs/node-token and read by the worker; after the worker joins, you may delete this file for security.
- SSH timeouts: Increase the boot timeout in the Vagrantfile or ensure your host has enough resources.

## Clean up

vagrant destroy -f

## What works

- Two-node K3s cluster (control plane + worker)
- K3s version: latest stable as of April 2026 (v1.34.6 used during development)
- Alpine Linux 3.18 guest
- Shared folders via VirtualBox (scripts and configuration)
